    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="ucb.00039.004_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place" rend="center">Washington D.C.</name>
                    <date when="1875-12-12">Dec 12<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>My Dear Walt Whitman:</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>When you were here I was closely confined to the desk, and did not find out till you were gone where you stopped. I was &amp; am very sorry I have missed you. Shortly I expect to be in <choice><abbr>Phila</abbr><expan>Philadelphia</expan></choice>&#8212;when I shall come over to Camden and find you.</p>
            
            <p>I am very glad to learn that you are as well as you are, &amp; that inspiration</p>
            
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="ucb.00039.003_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <!-- Whitman has written some prose on this page - unrelated to letter -->
            
            <pb xml:id="leaf002r" facs="ucb.00039.002_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            
            <p>still dwells with you. Conway's letter speaking of your new book is quite interesting. Will you let me know about if I can say something in adorance of its appearance. My brain will always do you homage &amp; my heart will bring love to you.</p>
            <p>Mrs H deserves rememberance. I have a book out, which I will send to-morrow. </p>
            <closer>
                <salute>Yours Always</salute>
                <salute>Affectionately</salute>
                <signed>Richard J. Hinton</signed>
            </closer>
            <postscript><p>Address me</p><p> Care "The Republic" W_D.C.</p></postscript>
            
            <pb xml:id="leaf002v" facs="ucb.00039.001_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <!-- This is the beginning of Whitman's prose on ucb.00039.003_large.jpg (above) -->
            
        </body>
